description:
I found this Salt Grass in Tecolote Canyon in San Diego, California.  This species of grass was located in the coastal sage scrub and chaparral environment of Southern California. Specifically, it was found on the side of a dirt trail in the canyon while the weather was partly cloudy and there was a slight breeze. The temperature was around 58°F and the soil conditions were sandy, silty, and dry. The grass was approximately 5 inches tall and spanned an area of 30 feet. 
 The grass has multiple splittings and is green and yellow in some areas.

description: I found this Wild Radish in Tecolote Canyon in San Diego, California.  This species of flowering plant was located in the coastal sage scrub and chaparral environment of Southern California.  Specifically, it was found on the side of a dirt trail in the canyon while the weather was partially cloudy and there was a slight breeze.  The temperature was around 58°F and the soil conditions were sandy, silty, and dry.  The plant was around 3 feet tall and spanned an area of 5-6 feet.  The plant has distinct white flowers with purple tips.  The flowers are around 1 inch in width and have four petals.

description: I found this Western Sycamore in Tecolote Canyon in San Diego, California.  This species of plane tree was located in the coastal sage scrub and chaparral environment of Southern California.  Specifically, it was found on the side of a dirt trail in the canyon while the weather was partially cloudy and there was a slight breeze.  The temperature was around 58°F and the soil conditions were sandy, silty, and dry.  The tree was around 20 feet tall and spanned an area of 50 feet.  The tree has dark green leaves that have five points, like half of a star.  The bark of the tree is a mixture of light and dark grey.  The tree also has 3-4 brown spiky balls that are attached to a string on the end of the branches of the tree.

This common nocturnal beetle was located in the coastal sage scrub and chaparral environment of Southern California.  Specifically, it was found in the middle of a dirt trail in the canyon while the weather was partially cloudy and there was a slight breeze. And yesterday I was at the library hoping to spot the red flanked blue tail, and I saw a flock. I said to the birder standing nearby that they’re one of my favorites, but I never see them at home. Then just this morning as I’m getting in my car to go to work, I hear that squeaky sound and only just registered it before closing my door to drive off!! A smallish flock in the neighbors tree. Scared off moments later by a marauding Cooper’s Hawk who I caught in flight!
